value.value: A monounsaturated fatty acid with a 24-carbon backbone and the sole double bond originating from the 9th carbon from the methyl end, with this bond in the cis- configuration.
A polyunsaturated long-chain fatty acid with an 18-carbon backbone and exactly 2 double bonds. There are numerous isomers and stereoisomers that can be called by this name.

A polyunsaturated long-chain fatty acid with an 18-carbon backbone and double bonds originating from the 3rd position and either the 6th or 7th position from the methyl end. There are at least 2 isomers that can be called by this name.
A recombinantly produced form of human nerve growth factor (NGF) protein with potential therapeutic application. Endogenous NGF can regulate neuronal proliferation, differentiation and survival.
A benign neoplasm that arises from the ciliated respiratory mucosa that lines the maxillary sinus.  It results from the invagination and proliferation of epithelial cells in the underlying stroma.

A polyunsaturated long-chain fatty acid with an 18-carbon backbone and double bonds originating from the 4th position and either the 7th position or the 8th position from the methyl end. There are at least 4 different stereoisomers that can be called by this name.

A polyunsaturated long-chain fatty acid with an 18-carbon backbone and double bonds originating from the 6th position and the 8th, 9th, 10th, 11th, 12th or 13th positions from the methyl end. The bond geometry of the molecule induces a kink in the main axis of the aliphatic chain at the n-6 position. There are at least 8 different isomers that can be called by this name.

A polyunsaturated long-chain fatty acid with an 18-carbon backbone and double bonds originating from the 9th position and the 11th, 12th, 13th or 14th positions from the methyl end. There are at least 7 different isomers that can be called by this name.
A polyunsaturated long-chain fatty acid with an 18-carbon backbone and exactly three double bonds. At least 17 different isomers of this compound are recognized.
A polyunsaturated long-chain fatty acid with an 18-carbon backbone and 4 double bonds originating from the 3rd, 5th, 7th and 9th positions from the methyl end.
A benign neoplasm that arises from the ciliated respiratory mucosa that lines the sphenoid sinus.  It results from the invagination and proliferation of epithelial cells in the underlying stroma.
A saturated fatty acid with a 15-carbon backbone. Pentadecylic acid is not normally synthesized by animals, but is found in trace amounts in dairy products.

A glycerol backbone covalently bound to a phosphate group in one position, and fatty acids in the 2nd and 3rd positions. Phosphatidic acids thus have a polar head and apolar tails, and occur in cell membranes throughout nature.
A phospholipid with a polar serine found in phosphoester linkage to diacylglycerol.
Any sterol found in the plant kingdom.

An ether lipid in which glycerol is covalently bound to a polar phospholipid head group like choline or ethanolamine, a typical ester-linked fatty acid, and an ether-linked fatty acid, which is usually a vinyl alcohol. Plasmalogens occur in nervous tissues, testes and kidneys at significant levels in vertebrates.
A benign neoplasm that arises from the ciliated respiratory mucosa that lines the frontal sinus.  It results from the invagination and proliferation of epithelial cells in the underlying stroma.

A polyunsaturated long-chain fatty acid with an 18-carbon backbone and exactly three double bonds, originating from the 5th, 7th and 9th positions from the methyl end, with these three bonds in the cis-, trans- and cis- configurations, respectively.

Any fully saturated phytosterol, indicating that the 5-6 bond of the sterol B ring has been oxidized. Saturated Phytosterols are in general produced by enzymatic hydrogenation of phytosterols. They are found in trace amounts in nuts, seed and legumes. Saturated phytosterols are not produced in the animal kingdom.
A monounsaturated fatty acid with a 24-carbon backbone and the sole double bond originating from the 9th carbon from the methyl end.
A class of dietary fatty acids that have an alkyl chain length from 2 up to 5 carbon atoms.

Any lipid derived from the aliphatic amino alcohol sphingosine, in which a single fatty acid is covalently bound to sphingosine via an amide linkage. Various ester-linked substituents can result in generation of ceramides, sphingomyelins and glycosphingolipids.
A saturated long-chain fatty acid with an 18-carbon backbone. Stearic acid is found in various animal and plant fats, and is a major component of cocoa butter and shea butter.

A steroid derivative characterized by the hydroxyl group in position C-3 of the steroid skeleton, and unsaturated bonds in position 5-6 of the B ring, and position 22-23 in the alkyl substituent. Stigmasterol is found in the fats and oils of soybean, calabar bean and rape seed, as well as several other vegetables, legumes, nuts, seeds, and unpasteurized milk.
A polyunsaturated fatty acid with a 24-carbon backbone and six double bonds. Three stereoisomers of Tetracosahexaenoic acid are recognized.
A benign neoplasm that arises from the ciliated respiratory mucosa that lines the ethmoid sinus.  It results from the invagination and proliferation of epithelial cells in the underlying stroma.

The free fatty acid (FFA) form of eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA), a polyunsaturated long-chain fatty acid found in fish oil with a 20-carbon backbone and 5 double bonds, with potential supplementing, anti-inflammatory, anti-thrombotic, immunomodulating, anti-angiogenic and chemopreventive activities. Upon administration of icosapent, the free form of EPA is incorporated in cell membrane phospholipids and replaces arachidonic acid. This inhibits arachidonic acid conversion into thromboxanes and prostaglandin E2 (PGE2).  Upon oral administration of icosapent, the EPA-FFA prevents and suppresses colonic neoplasia and reduces polyp formation and growth through as of yet not fully elucidated mechanisms.
Any steroid derivative bearing unsaturated bonds, typically found in position 5-6 of the B ring of the steroid skeleton.
A class of dietary fatty acids that have an alkyl chain length above 21 carbon atoms.
A benign epithelial neoplasm arising from the minor salivary glands in the hard palate. It is characterized by the presence of a monomorphic cellular infiltrate.
